# Overview

This is a healthcare appointment booking system with Node.js/Express backend, Next.js web frontend, and Flutter mobile app. The system manages doctor appointments, user authentication, and calendar availability.

## Code Review Checklist

Consider data flow and explain any new patterns and why they are used.

Note any changes that could affect infrastructure.

Account for empty, loading, error, and offline states in the UI.

Review frontend changes for accessibility (keyboard navigation, focus management, ARIA roles, color contrast).

For public API changes, ensure backward compatibility or increment the API version.

Avoid unnecessary dependencies; if a heavy dependency is added, consider inlining a minimal version.

Add high-quality tests; prefer integration tests for user flows over numerous low-quality tests.

Check for schema changes that may require a database migration.

Review changes to authentication flows or permissions; run a security review.

If using feature flags, determine if a new flag is needed for this change.

If i18n is set up, verify that new strings are localized and new routes are internationalized.

Identify places where caching could be used.

Ensure backend changes include critical observability and logging.

## Healthcare-Specific Rules

- All patient data handling must comply with healthcare privacy regulations
- Implement proper audit logging for all patient data access and modifications
- Use secure communication protocols for all healthcare-related data transmission
- Validate all medical appointment data thoroughly before processing
- Implement proper error handling that doesn't expose sensitive patient information
- Ensure appointment scheduling logic prevents double-booking and respects doctor availability
- Implement proper timezone handling for international healthcare providers
- Add rate limiting to prevent appointment booking abuse
- Use encrypted storage for all sensitive healthcare data
- Implement proper session management with automatic logout for security

## Architecture Rules

- Maintain separation between client, doctor, and admin user roles
- Use consistent API response formats across all endpoints
- Implement proper error boundaries in React components
- Use TypeScript interfaces for all data models across frontend and backend
- Follow RESTful API conventions for all backend routes
- Implement proper state management patterns in both web and mobile apps
- Use environment-specific configuration management
- Implement proper logging and monitoring for production deployments

## Development Practices

- Write meaningful commit messages following conventional commits format
- Use feature branches for all development work
- Implement comprehensive error handling and user feedback
- Test all user flows end-to-end before deployment
- Maintain consistent code formatting across all platforms
- Document all API endpoints and data models
- Implement proper version control for mobile app releases
